$$
\begin{array}{r l}&{=(S_{1}-S_{0})-(F_{1}-F_{0})=(\S90-\S100)-(\S90-\S100.25)=+\S0.25}\\ &{=(S_{1}-F_{1})-(S_{0}-F_{0})=b_{1}-b_{0}}\end{array}
$$  

In this example, the gain on the [futures](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%203%20-%20Futures%20Markets/Futures%20Not%20Subject%20to%20Cash-And-Carry.md) position is $\$10.25$ which more than o!sets the loss on the spot position of $\$10$ and hence the hedge is broadly successful. The proft from the hedged position depends on the change in the basis. The change in the basis is small because spot and [futures](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%203%20-%20Futures%20Markets/Futures%20Not%20Subject%20to%20Cash-And-Carry.md) prices are highly correlated. Thus the hedge position is much less risky than the unhedged position – since without the hedge the loss (or gain) would be the much larger amount $S_{1}-S_{0}$ . Note also that the ‘initial basis’ $b_{0}$ is known and ‘fxed’ at the outset of the hedge. It is the ‘fnal basis’ $b_{1}=S_{1}-F_{1}$ that is the source of uncertainty in the net proft.  

